Last Saturday we were happy to organise a special open day for the public to meet the breeding birds at our Ghadira Nature Reserve! Lots of families responded to our invitation to visit the reserve to see the newly-formed Black-winged Stilt and Little Ringed Plover families. Although our nature reserves are normally closed to the public in the summer months, we wanted to share this spectacle with the public. And those who visited were not disappointed, as clearly evidenced from these photos!

Day 93 - Athens: Managed to squeeze in a quick lunch before our train <U+0001F686>. One of the best trains we’ve had (if not the best!) on our travels <U+0001F60A>not only was it on time but incredibly clean and modern <U+0001F686><U+0001F601>. Also it provided some decent entertainment as there was a couple onboard having a domestic (and no it wasn’t @tommy_t26 and I for once <U+0001F92A>). We then went to a traditional Greek restaurant for dinner, Syntrimmi, where we had a few small plates and thought we were on to an absolute bargain, as they sold a litre of their organic house white wine for only €5. Unfortunately you get what you pay for and it turned out to be disgusting <U+0001F974>. We hoped it would improve as we drank it but it didn’t; luckily the waitress had only poured half a litre to stop it getting warm, so we managed to get the other half as red wine, which was much nicer! Sadly on our way home we saw a building on fire, with the fire brigade doing an amazing job of trying to save people. The smoke was so bad even from where we walked through, we hope everyone was ok. From our accommodation you can see the smoke from our balcony!

Mykonos is the Ibiza of Greece. A beautiful island in the Cyclades, which looks just like the postcards: white little houses with flowers and blue windows and doors, hand painted streets, windmills, pigeon keepers, chimneys, lots of little churches and wonderful restaurants and cafes. You can get here by air or ferry. I get by ferry and prices are between 30€ for economy slow ferry up to 120€ each way for speed ferry from athens, prices varies by season, u can get tickets online, travel agency or port. When u get here u can rent a scooter, ATV or car, if u come from usa like me u can rent only atv or car if dont have license for bike, I stayed in Artemidas village using @airbnb, very nice place and good price, close to town. When u get to town u get to see the #windmills, #littlevenice, eat and shop until drop dead with a million dollar view #mykonos #athens #greece #travelguide #travelblog #aroundtheworld #airbnb #mokinos #grecia #tips #chefcandy

DAY 6 #Greece. Spent the afternoon in #Fira town on #Santorini #shopping a bit. Walking the cliff look at all the packed in shops, having dinner and taking in the human and animal sites. Finally saw the #donkeystatiion that take folks up the hill from the #cruise ships. Not many experiences are authentic on #Santorini. Everything is geared toward the tourist. Even the workers are all from #Athens to take care of the tourists. I had a delightful meal then caught sight of the donkeys blocking the humans. Anyway #sunsets are magnificent and the Santorini stay dogs think that as well :) (last pic). Final stop #Athens. The days seem long here and my #vacation feels as if I have been at it for a month.

Odeão de Herodes Ático foi construído em 161 d.C pelo magnata ateniense Herodes Áticos em memória de sua esposa, Aspasia Annia Regilla. O telhado era de madeira de cedro, hoje inexistente, não tinha suporte inferior e era o que mais chamava a atenção de todos. Com capacidade para 5.000 expectadores, em 1950 foi reformado com mármore pentélico para atender ao público e desde então, tem sido o principal local do Festival de Atenas, que decorre de junho a setembro de cada ano. Em maio de 1962, Frank Sinatra deu dois concertos Benefit para a cidade de Atenas. Entre os artistas que se apresentaram no Odeão de Herodes Ático estão Plácido Domingo, José Carreras, Montserrat Caballé, Alicia de Larrocha, os Ballets Bolsho entre outros! <U+0001F1EC><U+0001F1F7><U+0001F9FF> #atenas #athens #grecia #greece #greecetravel #acropole #acropolis #vacation #ferias #viajar #trip #eurotrip #travelcouple #wanderlust #odeon #historicalplaces #odeonofherodesatticus

Visit at PCAI Residency and Collection. In conversation with Kika Kyriakakou Artistic Director of PCAI Residency, Collrction & Exhibitions Manager.

The Collection is based on special commissions mainly of moving image art. PCAI provides mid-career and emerging artists with the means and resources to create an artwork inspired by urgent environmental issues in their broader relation to current sociocultural, economic, philosophical concerns. The Collection invites artists to reflect on the concept of waste and related processes in a free and innovative way; to create art that challenges the limits of previous views and representations; to imagine new forms and use radical tactics while addressing our changing world. .

In celebration of Mary Magdalene’s Feast day, here are a few images of her from my recent travels. All of them subtly constellate a different aspect of her mythos. Come! Journey to this goddess with me <U+0001F33A>This first image is a beautiful Greek Orthodox Icon painted by an Athenian artist who is also a practitioner. He paints icons as spiritual practice. An incredible artist and deeply spiritual man, over the course of a few days, he spent many hours describing to me the layered symbolism hidden inside Greek iconography. <U+0001F33A> The second image is street art from Bologna. It’s not explicitly stated as MM, but to me the symbolism of the unction jar, the halo, and the semi-concealed gaze makes it clear that this is her. <U+0001F33A> The third is from a famous sculpture scene by Niccolò dell’Arca located at the Santa Maria della Vita church in Bologna. Emotional, evocative, and incredibly life-like! If you ever visit Bologna, this is not to be missed! <U+0001F33A> The fourth image is by Giovanni Gerolamo Savoldo and hangs in the Uffizi Gallery in Florence. What can I say other than, “The eternal feminine draws us forward” - From Goethe’s “Faust” #marymagdalene #mariamaddalena #mythology #archetype #uffizi #santamariadellavita #bologna #streetart #Athens #greekicon #faust #eternalfeminine #journeytothegoddess

Being a self confessed history nerd and a huge royalist, I couldn’t come to Malta without visiting the home that Her Majesty the Queen lived in with Prince Phillip, while he was stationed here in the Royal Navy. 
At the time she was know as Her Royal Highness Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh. 
The house was actually open today for the preview of an auction taking place this week, so it was possible to walk through the house. (Unfortunately they were super strict with a no photos policy though) 
It is hard to see the building and interior in such a poor state of repair though. .

This is a post about conservation of natural treasures, such as National Parks similar to Parnitha, Athens (Greece) . 12 years ago this beautiful fir tree forest was destroyed by a devastating fire. The fire burned about 25 milion square meters of forest. The forest never revived, even with few (failed) reforestation attempts. Ultimately, there was no clear constructive attempt to bring back the forest, probably due to low political will. As you see in the pictures, what is left is only low grass and some bushes. The lone black pine trees from an older reforestation attempt are infertile, as they need a higher altitudes to reproduce. It's just sad to walk by this beautiful place which brings life to 5+ million people and only few understand its significance. Please check WWFs video about the fire and if you are visiting Athens, try to take a respectful walk around the many magic paths Parnitha offers. #running #trailrunning #mountains #Parnitha #Athens #wwf @wwfgreece #nature #forest https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=O3Md37Wybvk

caption:
Day 1 - So that's day one done and dusted. To be perfectly honest, it's felt a lot longer than just one day. Time's blurring together as we've travelled from Melbourne to Doha to Athens, so it's hard to imagine it's just been ONE day.
But if I were to pick a city to spend my day through a jet-lagged delirium, Athens would be high up on that list.
A beautiful city. A truly beautiful city. We haven't even explored the mighty acropolis yet nor the rest of the Ancient Ruins, but that's for another time.
It was just so nice walking through the streets, hearing the mishmash of languages, seeing the red-tiled rooves, always seeing the Parthenon on the horizon. 
Athens is a beautiful city but it definitely has it's dark side too - I'd put it as a chaotic neutral. 
But overall, as I'm sitting at the bar of the hostel writing this, I'm excited to see what more this trip will have to offer.
Till tomorrow.

7 flights, 5 different airports, 3 high speed trains, 2 rental cars, 3 subway rides, multiple bus trips and endless miles walked, our Eurotrip has come to an end.
Total distance travelled is 18629kms in 15 days. (not including all the walking I forced the kids to do!!) I can’t even begin to count all the cool sights we’ve seen and views I’ve admired. 
Athens & Santorini, Greece. 
Naples, Sorrento, Positano, Amalfi, Ravello, Rome, Florence and Venice,  Italy. 
My boys have been so good and tolerant and curious and enjoyed every minute of it (and the pizza). I truly hope they keep their love for travel as they get older & never stop wanting to explore the world.  Travel is humbling. 
Every stop we’ve made has been more than I expected it to be and better than the last. I checked off so many items from my bucket list. I don’t want it to end. 
Greece and Italy you did not disappoint. I hope I’m lucky enough to visit again one day.  A piece of my heart will be left behind... As for travelling with only a carryon for 2 wks...the boys really enjoyed carrying around a bunch of my stuff (haha) and as you can see from most of my pics my hair and my wardrobe were the only things that suffered!! Where to next...

As mentioned in the prev video post, in our bus trip, we stopped at A3 station for Acropolis visit.
First thing u see once u enter this area is the Theater of Dionysus, being located on the south side of the Acropolis
.
.
.
The Theatre of Dionysus was used as a theatre from the sixth century BC onwards. 
It was the first and largest theatre to be built in Athens and could seat up to 17,000 people. 
It was dedicated to Dionysus, the Greek god of drama and wine and many other things <U+0001F644>
.
.
.
The history is not about the big picture but about the small details we framed .. enjoy!

Whenever ex navy or ex army guests visit Malta the team at P&A Sullivan include particular museums in their itinerary.
One of these venues is the old naval bakery, built in the 1840s  it now houses Malta's Maritime Museum. 
The museum has a collection of over 20,000 artifacts, and it is the largest museum on the island.Here one can find several well displayed exhibits including Roman Anchors, Traditional fishing boats, models of knights galleys and British naval vessels. One can also find displays of old navigational instruments log books and signal books. 
The Malta Maritime Museum at the Marina Grande in Vittoriosa is said to  help visitors chart 7,000 years of history under one roof.

Dwarfed by two sea monsters, these men and others have been training for many months for tomorrow’s yearly traditional Regatta.  Photos of my favourite team (Bormla/Cospicua) follow!  More photos showing a few of the beauty of our South come after.  These boat races will start tomorrow in the afternoon - 8th September is a national holiday in our Calendar referred to as Our Lady of Victories and Il-Bambina (the child girl) to honour the nativity of Mary, mother of Christ.  This grand feast commemorates three important Sieges:  The Great  Siege of Malta by the Ottoman Empire in 1565, The Siege by the French in 1800 and the Siege of Malta by the Italians ending in 1943.  Senglea which forms part of the Three Cities  feasts its Patron Saint Our Lady of Victories on this day.  This special feast is celebrated in other towns and villages both in Malta and Gozo but the greatest event lies right here!  I have so many childhood memories of my dad taking me to watch this competition.  He hailed from Bormla also known as Cospicua.  The photos I took today are from Bormla side and across the Laguna lies Senglea where the grand feast is taking place this weekend.  The last photo is an image of Mary - a portrait of the Statue which will be brought out of the Church tomorrow and taken around various streets in Senglea.  A few thousand people flock from all over Malta this weekend to be part of all of this.  Various teams from different places in Malta will compete tomorrow - and I am planning to go and watch.  Viva Bormla but may the best team win!

caption:
As I promised I will come up with some more pictures of Ellinikon Airport! It is located in Athens, right at the coastline of the Aegean Sea. It used to be the main airport of the Greek capital until it was replaced by Eleftherios Venizelos Airport in 2001. There have been multiple ideas of using the space for building tourist resorts but nothing really ever happened - also given by the financial crisis in Greece. We visited it in 2018 - It was majestic to see the Terminal once we arrived. It is falling apart but still somehow looked like it was closed just weeks ago! You might ask yourself if it's possible to sneak in.. Let's say it is possible.. and it also was our attention to do so.. Sadly a security guard showed up once we arrived at the airport. He was friendly though.. Allowed us to take as many pictures as we want through fences and windows but told that we shouldn't enter the terminal or apron! It was still amazing since there are plenty of aircraft left.. More about them the following days <U+0001F1EC><U+0001F1F7>

Greek connection <U+0001F9FF> Introducing new collab w/@durydava today <U+0001F31F> Their 1st double #LP is what I listened to the most this year. Instantly giving me shivers, hope, energy, genuinely creating some inner trippy reflexions each time I turn up the volume. The music could be in a #world #kraut #psych vein with a notable #punk identity. A deep brewing of vibes combining traditional #folk and 60s to 90s influences with a very modern original approach. Long psychedelic trips or global disorder are sung in #greek and the album also contains a mysterious title starting in #turkish called ""34522"" probably my favorite. The Athenian five piece band has a solid rhythm section exploring #free form of #music expression: soaring of clarinette, flute besides indian instrument like dilruba are combined with the famous bouzouki, essential element of greco-turkish folklore, mixed with wizardry guitar sounds & keys… The experiment is almost anthropologic, the live experience worthy to be lived.

caption:
Plato and Aristotle where already convinced about the spherical shape of the Earth. While Plato stated his conviction, he failed to give any  arguments for his belief. His student Aristorle did provide evidence, settling the matter once and for all. For instance, he pointed to the circular shadow of the Earth on the moon during the lunar eclipse and the changing altitude of stars when travelling far distances.
.
It is still commonly thought that is was Columbus who discovered the spherical shape of the Earth in the 15th century, when he sailed to America. In reality, however, the correct shape of the Earth had been discovered close to 2 millenia earlier. What Columbus does get credit for is the balsy decision to sail cross the Altantic Ocean with limited supplies.
.
.
.
The statue depicted is unfortunately not from Ancient Greece, but from modern times. But I liked it, so what the hell.
.

I’ve always been fascinated with historic sites (not museums, actual historic sites). This Cathedral forms the central part of the ancient fortified city of Gozo which housed the Gozo population in prehistoric times. Walking around this place allowed me to be transported back to the times when it was alive. The narrow passageways were filled with churches, market places, law courts, a hospital (for 12 women only) and even military buildings. A 360-degree of the city can be seen from the fort walls. This site is open 24 hours and is free for all. #mustvisit .

Which are your favourite Greek islands?? I have to say, Serifos was quite sublime and still rather untouched by mass tourism (and Brits) in a way that many of the other bigger Greek islands now are (I’m looking at you: Santorini, Mykonos, Zante, Rhodes, Corfu, Kos, Crete) However, even on those islands you’ll still find the tiny towns and villages that are a little bit more off the beaten track. Research prior to your trip pays dividends in a big way when you come to Greece. 
I planned and booked our trip myself, without a travel agent. It wasn’t easy... I guess the hardest part was picking an island. What to budget? For 11-nights, it’s cost around £700 pp for flights, ferry tickets, transfers and accommodation. (6-nights in Serifos, 5-nights in Athens) and then around £600 pp spends for food, drink and activities. We didn’t scrimp, so you could do it on much more of a shoestring budget if you needed to. The lovely thing about travel is that the memories you make take much longer than your tan to fade. 
Greece is most definitely one of my favourite countries for an island getaway. With Athens as a starting point you can never get bored — there’s around 2,000 islands to explore! 
Looking forward to sharing a write up of the trip itinerary and photos, for those of you hoping to explore Greece or the Greek Islands yourselves. Keep your eyes peeled to my stories for the post on lucieloves.co.uk — there’s also links to posts I’ve written about Skiathos, and an island hopping adventure to Mykonos, Naxos, Paros, Anti Paros & Santorini.

Uma dica importante para quem vai visitar o local: leve tudo o que você precisa para passar o dia, pois o local é extremamente afastado, praticamente no meio do nada. Ou seja, nenhum ambulante, nenhuma lojinha de souvenir, nenhum food-truck para matar a fome.

caption: Euro Trip - City 1: Athens. The capital city of Greece with a lot of historical architecture like Acropolis, Parthenon Temple.... Spectacular views of Athens from top of Acropolis... You can always make a quick stop at one of Athens oldest village near Acropolis called Plaka for some nice street food, desserts & souvlaki... If you plan to go any of the islands in Greece, plan a day at Athens because one it’s cheaper to travel through Athens and two you get to see one of the old wonders of thw world, Acropolis of Athens... It’s always super hot in Greece so pack your summer cloths with lot of sunscreen, caps & sunglasses with nice shoes because you gotta do some hiking to see the Acropolis... The best time to visit Greece is between May-September, but my advice would be to go between end of August to end of September to avoid the crazy summer... <U+0001F1EC><U+0001F1F7><U+0001F576><U+0001F452><U+0001F45F><U+0001F975><U+0001F491><U+2600><U+FE0F><U+0001F525> #europetravel #eurotrip #honeymoon #greece #athens #acropolis #travelblogger #ForeverA<U+2764><U+FE0F>N #ourtravelgram #vancityblogger #traveldiaries #travelguide #travelgram

Acts 17 tells of Paul’s first time there and the conversation he had with all the peeps on Mars Hill. We were on Mars Hill today (Chad on mars hill, lol)!
